          },
          "message": "Yes. The hooks now write to one aggregate file only: [.github/logs/copilot-history.json](/home/tirth/tirth/Co-pilot%20Sessions/hrflow-backend/.github/logs/copilot-history.json). I updated both hook scripts, [log-message.sh](/home/tirth/tirth/Co-pilot%20Sessions/hrflow-backend/.github/hooks/scripts/log-message.sh) and [log-session-end.sh](/home/tirth/tirth/Co-pilot%20Sessions/hrflow-backend/.github/hooks/scripts/log-session-end.sh), so they append into that single JSON file, auto-stage that file, and leave it read-only after each write. I also migrated the existing split session logs into the aggregate file and removed the old per-session files, so the logs folder now contains only that one file.\n\nI validated the scripts, ran a simulated session against the new setup, and confirmed the real file ends with read-only permissions in the repo. One caveat: this is read-only by filesystem mode, not truly immutable. Anyone with local write privileges can still change permissions back. If you want stronger enforcement than that, the next step would be a CI or pre-commit check that rejects edits outside the hooks, or a Linux-specific immutable-bit workflow, though that would need extra handling because the hooks themselves must still be able to write.",
